# Minecart route-stop marker implementation checklist

## Goal

When the native Minecart Routes menu is open, allow the player to select a
route and identify its stops on the fortress map. The selected route must draw
a marker at each stop's map position and label the marker with the stop's
custom name.

## Confirmed native boundaries

- [ ] Treat `dwarfmode/Hauling` as the production focus path for the native
      Minecart Routes menu.
- [ ] Read route and stop data from `df.global.plotinfo.hauling`.
- [ ] Resolve route identity from `df.hauling_route.id` and resolve markers
      from the selected route's ordered `stops` vector.
- [ ] Read each label and position directly from `df.hauling_stop.name` and
      `df.hauling_stop.pos`.
- [ ] Treat `view_routes`, `view_stops`, and `scroll_position` as the native
      flattened menu-row model.
- [ ] Do not use the removed `hauling.cursor_top` field or the stale accessor
      in `gui/guide-path.lua`.
- [ ] Do not infer route identity from localized text, rendered route names,
      or pointer proximity to a map stop.
- [ ] Do not assume Premium DF exposes a persistent selected-route field;
      DwarfUI owns the selected route ID.

## Scope and behavior contract

- [ ] Select a route when the player clicks a visible native route header or
      one of that route's visible stop rows.
- [ ] Preserve the selected route while the player scrolls the route list,
      pans the map, or changes z-levels.
- [ ] Pass route-list clicks through to native DF after observing them so
      existing route-menu actions continue to work.
- [ ] Draw a visible selection indicator beside the selected route header when
      that header is visible.
- [ ] Clear selection when the selected route is deleted, the world unloads,
      the overlay is disabled, or the Hauling menu closes.
- [ ] Re-resolve the selected numeric route ID against the current route vector
      before every render; do not retain a native route pointer across frames.
- [ ] Reflect stop additions, removals, renames, and position changes without
      reopening the menu or reselecting the route.
- [ ] Draw same-z stops as solid markers at their exact map tiles.
- [ ] Draw off-z stops whose x/y coordinates are within the viewport as
      visually distinct projected markers with an explicit signed z delta.
- [ ] Never present an off-z projection as though it were a stop on the
      currently displayed z-level.
- [ ] Do not change the map viewport, cursor, route definitions, or stop data
      merely to display markers.
- [ ] Keep this work independent from editing an existing route-stop position,
      which remains a separate project item.

## Phase 0: Build the route-selection model

- [ ] Add a production module for route lookup, flattened-row resolution, and
      selected-route lifecycle rules.
- [ ] Represent stateful model types as proper `defclass` classes.
- [ ] Isolate native route-list geometry and focus decisions behind a
      documented route-menu layout class.
- [ ] Store only the selected route ID as persistent selection state.
- [ ] Resolve clicks on route headers and stop rows to their owning route.
- [ ] Ignore clicks outside the native route list and clicks in unsupported
      nested contexts.
- [ ] Ensure selection observation returns `false` or `nil` so native DF still
      processes the same input.
- [ ] Clear stale selection when no route with the selected ID exists.
- [ ] Add table-driven unit tests for zero-based vectors, scrolling, route
      headers, stop rows, list boundaries, invalid rows, and stale IDs.
- [ ] Add regression coverage proving duplicate route names and duplicate stop
      names do not affect identity.
- [ ] Add LuaDoc comments to every new or modified class and method.

### Phase 0 completion gate

- [ ] Selection is deterministic from native row data and numeric route IDs.
- [ ] Native route-menu input remains unconsumed.
- [ ] The focused model tests pass with no live DF dependency.

## Phase 1: Build stop-marker projection and label layout

- [ ] Add a projection class that consumes a selected route and a
      `gui.dwarfmode.Viewport` and produces immutable marker descriptors.
- [ ] Preserve the route's stop ordering and include the stop ID, display
      index, name, world position, screen position, and signed z delta in each
      descriptor.
- [ ] Use `Viewport:isVisible()` for same-z markers and
      `Viewport:isVisibleXY()` for explicitly marked off-z projections.
- [ ] Use `Viewport:tileToScreen()` for map projection instead of deriving
      screen positions from `window_x`, `window_y`, or UI text coordinates.
- [ ] Define distinct pens or graphics tiles for same-z, above, and below
      markers with text-mode fallbacks.
- [ ] Include the custom stop name in every label and include a signed z delta
      for every off-z label.
- [ ] Keep labels within the visible map viewport by choosing left or right
      placement and truncating only when neither direction has enough room.
- [ ] Resolve overlapping labels deterministically without moving the marker
      away from its stop tile.
- [ ] Avoid drawing labels over native non-map panels.
- [ ] Add unit tests for same-z, above, below, offscreen, map-edge, long-name,
      empty-name, duplicate-position, and collision cases.

### Phase 1 completion gate

- [ ] Every visible same-z stop produces one exact-tile marker and one label.
- [ ] Every visible-x/y off-z stop is unmistakably identified as a projection.
- [ ] Marker and label layout remains inside the map viewport at all tested
      screen edges and interface sizes.

## Phase 2: Integrate the registered DFHack overlay

- [ ] Add a production `overlay.OverlayWidget` registered for the Hauling
      viewscreen and restricted to the intended focus paths.
- [ ] Use a fullscreen host only for screen-wide hit testing and map drawing;
      do not expose a meaningless movable frame.
- [ ] Construct and own the route-selection, menu-layout, and marker-projection
      classes from the overlay.
- [ ] Observe route-list clicks in `onInput()` and pass all native inputs
      through unless a future DwarfUI-owned control explicitly requires
      consumption.
- [ ] Render the native screen first, then draw the selected-route indicator,
      map markers, and stop labels.
- [ ] Use the supported map painter mode or DFHack map-overlay API so markers
      render correctly in both graphics and text modes.
- [ ] Avoid per-frame world scans; inspect only the selected route and its
      stops.
- [ ] Register the overlay module in DwarfUI's module registry and reload
      lifecycle.
- [ ] Update package-contract tests for every new production module and asset.
- [ ] Verify `dwarfui reload` removes the old class/module instances and
      registers the new overlay exactly once.

### Phase 2 completion gate

- [ ] The overlay appears in DFHack's overlay registry and is enabled according
      to its declared default/configuration.
- [ ] Selecting, scrolling, panning, changing z-levels, renaming stops, and
      deleting the selected route leave no stale marker or duplicated overlay.
- [ ] Native route editing behavior remains functional after overlay input
      interposition.

## Phase 3: Add component and production-boundary coverage

- [ ] Add a DwarfSpec file whose filename ends only in `.ds.lua`; do not use
      `_spec` or any additional test suffix.
- [ ] Mount the production overlay class, not a test-only proxy.
- [ ] Back the mounted component with the real native Hauling viewscreen and
      real `plotinfo.hauling` route data.
- [ ] Position the DwarfSpec pointer over an actual rendered native route row
      and click it through the component input boundary.
- [ ] Assert that the clicked `view_routes` route ID becomes selected while the
      native screen still receives the click.
- [ ] Center a reversible test viewport on a real selected-route stop and
      assert that the marker occupies the screen tile produced by
      `Viewport:tileToScreen(stop.pos)`.
- [ ] Assert that the rendered label contains the actual native
      `df.hauling_stop.name` value.
- [ ] Change to a different z-level and verify the same native stop becomes an
      explicitly directional projection rather than a same-z marker.
- [ ] Scroll the actual route list, click a newly visible route or stop row,
      and verify selection follows the native flattened row model.
- [ ] Verify route deletion or fixture invalidation clears the marker state.
- [ ] Snapshot and restore viewport, cursor, overlay selection, route-menu
      scroll state, and any other changed UI state even when an assertion
      fails.
- [ ] Keep the prepared-save requirement explicit when no suitable minecart
      route and stop exist.
- [ ] If deletion or rename coverage requires mutation, create a disposable
      test route and restore or remove only that fixture; never mutate an
      existing player-owned route for automated coverage.

### Phase 3 completion gate

- [ ] The component test proves that interaction with the actual rendered DF
      Hauling menu selects the expected real route.
- [ ] Marker coordinates and text are derived from the same real native stop,
      not from duplicated fixtures.
- [ ] DwarfSpec reports confirmed cleanup with no retained screen, subject,
      pointer patch, viewport change, or route mutation.

## Phase 4: Validate packaging and live behavior

- [ ] Run the focused route-selection and marker-layout unit tests.
- [ ] Run the focused DwarfSpec native-menu component test through
      `tools/Run-AutomationTests.ps1`, which must only pass its arguments
      through to `dwarfspec run`.
- [ ] Run the complete standalone unit suite.
- [ ] Run the complete DwarfSpec suite through the same pass-through wrapper.
- [ ] Run Lua syntax validation for production, unit, support, and `.ds.lua`
      files.
- [ ] Run the offline build and verify the expanded package contents.
- [ ] Run archive package verification.
- [ ] Run `git diff --check`.
- [ ] Install the packaged mod into the configured live DFHack instance and run
      `dwarfui reload`.
- [ ] Confirm the live overlay registry contains exactly one enabled
      route-marker widget with the expected Hauling focus restriction.
- [ ] In the prepared fortress, click real route headers and stop rows and
      visually confirm selection indicators, exact-tile markers, custom names,
      list scrolling, map panning, same-z markers, and off-z projections.
- [ ] Rename and delete a disposable selected route or stop through native DF
      and verify markers update or clear without errors; do not use an
      existing player-owned route for this destructive check.
- [ ] Review the DFHack console and logs for Lua errors after selection,
      scrolling, rendering, reload, rename, and deletion checks.
- [ ] Record automated, packaged, registered-overlay, and manual visual
      evidence separately.

### Phase 4 completion gate

- [ ] Focused and complete unit and DwarfSpec suites pass with zero failures.
- [ ] Syntax, offline build, expanded package, archive package, and diff checks
      pass.
- [ ] Live DFHack proves overlay discovery, reload, native route-row selection,
      map rendering, and cleanup without overstating component-test coverage.

## Definition of done

- [ ] Clicking an actual native route header or stop row selects the correct
      route without blocking the native menu action.
- [ ] The selected route remains identified after route-list scrolling and map
      navigation.
- [ ] Every selected-route stop visible on the current z-level has an exact
      map-tile marker and its current custom name.
- [ ] Every selected-route stop projected from another z-level is explicitly
      marked as above or below with the correct signed delta.
- [ ] Route and stop edits are reflected without stale pointers, stale labels,
      duplicate overlays, or reopening the menu.
- [ ] The implementation uses documented DFHack viewport and overlay APIs and
      performs no world scan during rendering.
- [ ] All new and modified classes and methods have LuaDoc comments.
- [ ] Unit tests, real-native-menu DwarfSpec coverage, syntax checks, packaging
      checks, overlay-registration proof, and live visual proof are recorded
      independently.

